7. CONCEPTS — WHAT YOU ACTUALLY LEARNED
Firmware flashing
Flashing replaces the factory firmware on the ESP32 with Marauder. Same chip, new OS. Identical concept to reimaging a machine. The four .bin files map to specific memory addresses — bootloader, partition table, boot app, and main firmware. Each must go to the correct address or the device will not boot.
hostapd vs dnsmasq
hostapd creates the access point — it makes the Pi broadcast a Wi-Fi SSID. dnsmasq handles DHCP — when your tablet connects, dnsmasq assigns it an IP address from the range 192.168.4.2-20. Without dnsmasq, devices connect but get no IP and cannot communicate.
Why the IP kept disappearing
NetworkManager claimed wlan0 before hostapd could assign the static IP. dhcpcd.conf told the system what IP to use, but NetworkManager ignored it and connected to the home router instead. The fix was manually assigning the IP with 'ip addr add' and then making that permanent via rc.local so it runs on every boot.
Serial communication
The ESP32 appears as /dev/ttyUSB0 when plugged into the Pi. This is a serial device — the Pi and ESP32 talk via UART over USB at 115200 baud. The 'screen' command opens a terminal session over that serial link. This is the same protocol used in industrial equipment, PLCs, and legacy SCADA systems.
SHA256 and why it matters
When SSH shows a host fingerprint SHA256 hash, it is asking you to verify you are connecting to the correct machine and not an impersonator (MITM attack). If the hash changes unexpectedly, something is wrong. You verified this instinctively because of Security+ prep — that knowledge is already operational.
